Please remember that due to COVID-19 we have a limited seating capacity.

post_text: It's heartwarming to see our community encouraging students to read and learn!
shared_text:
Miss Beckwith's Class added a new photo to the album: 2020-2021.
September 15 at 6:48 PM ·

My homeroom class got to receive their sponsor books today! My second block class should be receiving them soon but I’m waiting on a few more to arrive first.

What is a “sponsor book?” This is my third year doing what I call “Sponsor a Student.”￼￼ I reach out on social media asking if anyone would like to sponsor a student. What a sponsor is signing up to do is to purchase a book for a student￼ and send them well wishes throughout the year. Many sponsors also write notes of encouragement inside the book if they are able to. Sponsors have been from all over the United States! The students get to keep the book at the end of the year, and it is a reminder that they will always have people that believe in them no matter what!￼￼

Thank you sponsors! We appreciate you!

#bastropisd #teacher #sponsorastudent
Bastrop ISD LPE Community

September 9 at 1:07 PM ·

Our NIBBLES: The Nutrition in Backpacks before Little Ones Exit School (NIBBLES) the program provides weekend meals and snacks during the school year for 142 children from low-income families at Lost Pines Elementary, Red Rock Elementary and Bastrop Intermediate schools. With 1 in 4 Bastrop County children going hungry, we are serving just the tip of the iceberg. We want to serve more of the thousands of hungry children, but we need your help. Consider making a donation to help a student in need.

post_text: Taking the census matters for our community for so many reasons. But here’s an additional incentive if you needed one!
shared_text:
Count Me In Bastrop County
September 6 at 10:00 AM ·

Complete the 2020 United States Census Online, and You Could Win $500!
1. Complete your 2020 Census ONLINE at www.my2020census.gov before September 30th.
2. Take a screenshot of your Census completion page and email it to census@bastropcares.org to receive 2 entries.
3. BONUS ROUND! Refer a neighbor or friend, and if they mention your name and email when they submit their census to the contest, you will receive one additional entry per referral.
4. Want to play, but already taken the census? NO PROBLEM! You can still receive entries through the referrals option mentioned above.
One lucky winner will receive a $500 Visa Gift Card with a $100 Visa Gift Card for the runner-up.
Like and share the ‘Count Me In Bastrop County’ Facebook page where winners will be drawn LIVE on October 1st.
No purchase necessary. Entrants must be residents of Bastrop County and have completed their census after September 4th, 2020. This contest is sponsored by Bastrop County Cares and made possible through grant funding. Bastrop County Cares is a registered 501(c)(3) non-profit organization.

No purchase necessary. Entrants must be residents of Bastrop County and have completed their census after September 4th, 2020. This contest is sponsored by Bastrop County Cares and made possible through grant funding. Bastrop County Cares is a registered 501(c)(3) non-profit organization.

Be part of the initiative to improve internet access in Bastrop County sponsored by Bastrop County Cares. To take the 10-minute survey as a resident, business owner or designated representative of an organization, please go to:

https://www.myconnectedcommunity.org/bastrop-county/

Can't go online to take the survey? Pick up a paper copy at any of these locations:

• Bastrop County Courthouse Annex, 804 Pecan Street, Bastrop TX
• Bastrop County Elgin Annex, 704 Bull Run Road, Elgin TX
• Bastrop County Cedar Creek Annex, 5540 FM 535, Cedar Creek TX
• Bastrop County Smithville Annex, 1624 NE Loop 230, Smithville TX

For more information about this broadband initiative or the Bastrop County Broadband Committee, please email info@bastropcares.org. This was made possible by St. David’s Foundation.

shared_text:
Count Me In Bastrop County
August 11 at 10:00 AM ·

You Could Win $500 by Completing the U.S. Census Bureau Online Today!

1. Complete your Census online at www.my2020census.gov between August 10th and August 30th, 2020.

2. Take a screenshot of your Census completion page and email it to census@bastropcares.org.

3. Like and share the “Count Me In Bastrop County” Facebook page using the hashtag #BastropCountyCounts

4. Names will be drawn live online on September 1st – the winner will win a $500 Visa Gift Card, and the runner up will win a $100 Visa Gift Card.

Entrants must be residents of Bastrop County and have completed their census after August 10th, 2020. No purchase necessary. Sponsored by Bastrop County Cares and made possible though grant funding. Bastrop County Cares is a registered 501 (c) (3).

Please join us in welcoming Emily Allen to the principal's role at Mina Elementary School. She has proudly served as the school's assistant principal since 2015. Click here for the full story: https://bit.ly/3ho6Xam

"I’m so honored to continue my career as the Principal of Mina Elementary, a school that has been my home for the past five years. I have strong relationships with my colleagues and our families, and I know the high expectations we have set for ourselves. I will continue the proud traditions that make Mina Elementary a wonderful school and seek new heights together for amazing students," Allen said.

BISD will start the 2020-21 school year with virtual instruction for all students for the first three weeks. The safety and well-being of our students and staff is of utmost importance to us, and we believe this 3-week transitional start affords us the greatest flexibility in creating a safe and secure learning and working environment.

You can find the message emailed to parents from Superintendent Edwards on our Back to School Planning hub: https://www.bisdtx.org/domain/3966

The safety and well-being of our students and staff is of utmost importance to us, and we believe this 3-week transitional start affords us the greatest flexibility in creating a safe and secure learning and working environment.

You can find the message emailed to parents from Superintendent Edwards on our Back to School Planning hub: https://www.bisdtx.org/domain/3966

post_text:
We are so proud to announce Reba King as Bastrop ISD's new Director of Early Literacy. She will lead the district's literacy programming in grades PK through 1st grade for all six elementary schools. Click here for the full story: https://bit.ly/2Z8PtXZ

“We are thrilled to welcome Reba as the Director of Early Literacy,” said Superintendent Barry Edwards. “Her experience in elementary education and campus administration establishes a strong framework to succeed in this new role and to tackle the challenge of ensuring that our youngest learners excel in language development, vocabulary, reading, and writing. She has a deep understanding of students’ needs and will work tirelessly to make sure those needs are addressed.”

post_text: The Bastrop ISD Health Center opens Monday, June 15 for BISD students and their siblings. This pediatric clinic is accepting both telehealth and in-person visits. The clinic is located inside of the BISD Family Resource Center at 1602 Hill Street. Entrance is on Cedar Street. This is a partnership with Community Health Centers of South Central Texas and Bluebonnet Trails.

UPDATE 11:29 am - The BISD feeding sites at schools, mobile sites, and bus routes have closed due to severe thunderstorms and weather warnings and we will be unable to serve any remaining meals today. We apologize for this inconvenience.

Certain portions of the county (Cedar Creek, Red Rock, Rosanky, etc.) are under tornado warning from a severe thunderstorm coming from the Lockhart area. Mobile feeding sites will be delayed until the storm has passed. Regular feeding sites are sheltering in place indoors. Please follow all weather warnings.

post_text: Help Bastrop County Cares and Connected Nation identify the true picture of internet connectivity in our area for our homes, businesses, and schools.
shared_text:
Bastrop County Cares
May 1 at 9:42 AM ·

How’s your internet? One of the major problems in rural communties like Bastrop is the lack of effective connectivity, which can negatively impact all community members, business and development decisions as well as grant opportunities.

Connected Nation Texas is asking for community feedback in order to get better data on internet service .ake 5 minutes to check your speed and let them know whether or not the maps are correct!

This is a 2 step process.

1. First, find your home or business on the Preliminary maps. There is an interactive map at https://connectednation.org/texas/interactivemap or you can download maps at https://connectednation.org/texas/mapping-analysis/ . Do the maps show what is actually available in your home or business? You can check your speed here - https://beta.speedtest.net/

2. Give feedback on the maps at https://connectednation.org/texas/feedback.

WE'RE EXPANDING!
Beginning Monday, April 6 we are adding 13 bus stops to our meal distribution program, bringing the total # of locations to receive meals to 21 sites. To improve efficiency, we have also adjusted the hours of all of our school-based and mobile feeding sites to be 9:00 am to 12:00 pm. Check the flyer for all the sites and hours. We look forward to serving you! #BeSafe #BeResponsible #StayHomeTexas

¡ESTAMOS AMPLIANDO!
A partir del lunes 6 de abril, agregaremos 13 paradas de autobús a nuestro programa de distribución de comidas, con lo que el número total de ubicaciones para llevar comidas a 21 sitios. Para mejorar la eficiencia, también hemos ajustado las horas de todos nuestros sitios de alimentación escolar y móvil para que sean de 9:00 a.m. a 12:00 p.m. Consulte el volante para todos los sitios y horarios. ¡Esperamos poder servirle!

post_text: Looking for ways to help during this crisis. Consider our local food pantry!
shared_text:
Bastrop County Emergency Food Pantry & Support Center, Inc.
March 23 at 2:56 PM ·

The Bastrop County Emergency Food Pantry & Support Center strives to serve Bastrop County residents in crisis—especially now during the Covid-19 Pandemic.

⬆️ This month, the Pantry experienced a 39% increase in request for services as a result of job loss and/or reduced income.

Are you interested in offering support for the most vulnerable members of the community, like the seniors that participate in our Brown Bag program?

You can make a donation today!

👉🏻Your donation of cash or by check can be dropped off at 806 Fayette Street Bastrop, TX or mailed to PO 953 Bastrop, TX 78602.

👉🏻To donate by credit card or PayPal donations, please click the button below:

👉🏻https://www.bastropfoodpantry.org/donate/donate-cash/

post_text:
March 13 - In the interest of student and staff health safety, Bastrop ISD has cancelled school events and activities until further notice. The only activity still proceeding is the official UIL contest for choir at Hays CISD scheduled for today. We await word of any changes to this contest from Texas UIL. SCHOOL IS OPEN for teaching and learning, and we look forward to seeing all of our students today.

District administration will continue to closely monitor the situation in coordination with local and state health officials and provide operational updates, as necessary.

Students, parents, and staff are urged to remain vigilant in their efforts to stay healthy. Thank you for your cooperation as we ensure that Bastrop ISD is safe and healthy.

Emile Elementary PTA and campus administrators celebrated the lives of two people the school recently lost.
The PTA bought a tree and planted it in memory of Christa Reid, an Emile teacher who passed away last year. The tree was planted in front of the school.
The PTA also donated a Buddy Bench in memory of a student who was taken too young.
The bench is located on the school playground for students to enjoy and spend time together.

post_text: KNOW THE FACTS...Did you know that nearly 84% of Bastrop ISD's budget goes directly into the classroom for things like teachers, counselors, curriculum, instructional materials, library books, and more? Bond money cannot be used for these things. For a District to do capital improvements, build new schools, or purchase technology or new school buses, a District must go to the voters in a bond election. To learn more about Bastrop ISD's bond election, visit https://www.bisdtx.org/bond2020
shared_text:
Bond 2020 / Bond 2020
In the fall of 2019, a Citizens Advisory Task Force, made up of 59 community members studied, analyzed, and weighed the current and future needs of the district. Based on the committee’s recommendations, the Bastrop ISD Board of Trustees called for a $140,159,000 bond election to be held on May 2...

Based on the committee’s recommendations, the Bastrop ISD Board of Trustees called for a $140,159,000 bond election to be held on May 2...

post_text: KNOW THE FACTS ... The BISD school bond was developed by a diverse group of 59 of your neighbors who spent hundreds of hours analyzing and weighing the current and future needs of the district. These community members are moms and dads, grandparents, business owners, pastors, teachers, retirees, PTA members and more who live all throughout the BISD boundaries. We appreciate their hard work and sacrifice! The result was a $140,159,000 bond that was unanimously approved by the Bastrop ISD School Board. The election is May 2. To learn more, visit bisdtx.org/bond2020.
shared_text:
Bond 2020 / Bond 2020
In the fall of 2019, a Citizens Advisory Task Force, made up of 59 community members studied, analyzed, and weighed the current and future needs of the district. Based on the committee’s recommendations, the Bastrop ISD Board of Trustees called for a $140,159,000 bond election to be held on May 2...

post_text: Our NJROTC Cadets listened intently as Captain Becky Bates talked about her career and the path it has taken her on. Capt. Bates is a 27 year veteran of the Navy and is a Naval Aerospace and Operational Physiologist. In the Navy, she works with aviators training them in aeromedical aspects of flight, sensory physiology, aviation life support systems, acceleration physiology, emergency egress, and land and water survival.

post_text: This FREE event is tomorrow night! You won't want to miss it.
shared_text:
St. David's Foundation
January 22 at 10:37 AM ·

We are proud to support "Healing History" - a series of community conversations and music that is starting this Friday evening, presented by Bastrop County Cares. This series is aimed at creating healing conversations and high-quality musical experiences to overcome the cross-cultural miscommunication that permeates our societal systems. It is through shared human experiences that we desire to create inclusive approaches to resilience and the arts. Healing History will work from a trauma-informed perspective to guide change for Bastrop County.

Emile Elementary School is part of a nationwide movement to remember our fallen US Soldiers. Thanks to nine generous sponsors, the school was able to donate more than 40 wreaths to Wreaths Across America. Emile's donation was part of the 57,000 wreaths placed at Fort Sam Houston National Cemetery in San Antonio.
Part of the goal is to teach students about giving and understanding the value of freedom.

UPDATE: 8:23 am - Aqua Water has indicated there is NO BOIL WATER NOTICE for any campus or for the area. We do anticipate having school at CCHS and BES tomorrow, but we will update later today.

Due to a pipeline break of Aqua Water Supply, there will be no school today, December 5 for CCHS or BES. A message went to parents via call and text. Students already on buses will be received at those campuses while arrangements can be made to get them back home. The remainder of bus routes for CCHS are cancelled. Parents who have the ability to pick up their children who are at Bluebonnet should do so.

post_text: Today at Red Rock Elementary, 24 students are on a mission to go to Mars. It's part of the school's R.I.S.E. program, which is funded through a BEF grant. R.I.S.E stands for Red Rock Interplanetary Space Exploration. For the past 12 weeks, these students have practiced and learned about space exploration. The goal of the program is to encourage students to do more STEM activities and use critical thinking to solve problems. Until midnight tonight, the students who are wearing NASA space costumes, will work out of makeshift shuttles in classrooms. Parents of the students will work in Mission Control. The 24 students picked for the mission wrote a 300 word essay about why they wanted to participate in this program.

post_text: After months of planning, the Stony Point Community in Bastrop officially has a new playground. It took a village to make this project happen. There have been months of planning meetings, community input, and playground designs by students from Bluebonnet Elementary School. On Saturday it all culminated with nearly two hundred volunteers coming together to build the playground. Partnerships with KaBOOM!, @BastropCares, @stdavidsfoundation, Bastrop County, and the community made all this possible. We truly live in a special place.

post_text: Teaching math while doing a fun activity. #LearningIsFun
shared_text:
Bastrop ISD Community Relations
October 18, 2019 at 9:00 AM ·

This morning our youngest learners at the Emile Child Development Center mixed up their own batch of playdough.

The students and teachers in Toddler 2 worked on math skills (measuring ingredients) and gross motor development (large movements). Students made snakes, tortillas, and balls by manipulating the play dough in their hands with the assistance of the teachers.

This is an easy activity you can do at home as well!

Playdough Ingredients:
1 cup flour
1/2 cup salt
1 T. Massage oil
1/2 cup of water

Combine all ingredients and mix well to playdough consistency.

If you want to add some color you can add tumeric for yellow, paprika for orange, blueberry juice for blue, or food coloring.

Bastrop Touchdown Club
October 9, 2019 at 11:15 AM ·

We are excited to announce that our 🐻 Bear Spirit Shop trailer received a facelift!! 🤗 This puts us another step closer to being able to bring spirit 📣 gear to you which benefits our 🏈 program!! Win-win!
Next up, fixing up the inside and then we will be ready to roll!! Make sure you watch our Facebook page for updates on 📍locations and new 👚 merchandise!

A big shout 📣 out to Outlaw Truck Outfitters for the shiny new fenders & tires, Bastrop Signs & Banners for the decals, Sign and Banner Texas for the TD Club artwork and to Spiradrill for the generous donations!! We couldn’t have done this without all of you and the support of the Bear Nation community in this #maroonout movement! 👊 We are so thankful for all the Bear fans that want to see this town painted maroon, white and proud!! 👊
We ❤️ it!!
